	  <title>Linear Independence, Facts: Examples</title>
	
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Show that any collection of two or more vectors in <math>
                  <latex>\RNr</latex>
               </math> is linearly dependent.</para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme type="Solution">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>To see that any collection of two or more vectors in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr</latex>
                     </math> is linearly dependent we use that part iii. of the 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>lemma</hot>
                        <crossref>
                           <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_LinearIndependenceFacts"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>Look up this fact</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </crossref>
                     </subordinate>. Then we observe that <math>
                        <latex>\RNr</latex>
                     </math> is spanned by a single vector, for example <math>
                        <latex>\StdBss{1} = (1)</latex>
                     </math>. So if any collection of vectors in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr</latex>
                     </math> is to be linearly independent, the number of vectors in the collection must be 0 or 1. Accordingly, a collection of two or more vectors in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr</latex>
                     </math> is linearly dependent.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
	
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Show that any collection of three or more vectors in <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
               </math> is linearly dependent.</para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme type="Solution">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>To see that any collection of three or more vectors in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> is linearly dependent we use that part iii. of the 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>lemma</hot>
                        <crossref>
                           <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_LinearIndependenceFacts"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>Look up this fact</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </crossref>
                     </subordinate>. Indeed, we observe that <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> is spanned by a two vectors, for example <math>
                        <latex>\StdBss{1} = (1,0)</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\StdBss{2}=(0,1)</latex>
                     </math>. This is so because every vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}=(a,b)</latex>
                     </math> in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> may be expressed as the linear combination</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.array column="3">
                  <row xmlns:compositor="Compositor" compositor:rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>(a,b)</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>a\cdot \StdBss{1} + b\cdot \StdBss{2}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
               </math.array>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>So if any collection of vectors in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> is to be linearly independent, the number of vectors in the collection must be less than or equal to 2. Accordingly, a collection of three or more vectors in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>
                     </math> is linearly dependent.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
	
	
	  <showme>
		    <statement.showme>
			      <para>
            <para.body>Show that any collection of four or more vectors in <math>
                  <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
               </math> is linearly dependent.</para.body>
         </para>
		    </statement.showme>
		    <answer.showme type="Solution">
         <answer.showme.block>
            <answer.showme.block.body>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>To see that any collection of four or more vectors in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> is linearly dependent we use that part iii. of the 
				<subordinate>
                        <hot>lemma</hot>
                        <crossref>
                           <theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_LinearIndependenceFacts"/>
                           <info>
						
						                        <para>
                                 <para.body>Look up this fact</para.body>
                              </para>
					                      </info>
                        </crossref>
                     </subordinate>. Indeed, we observe that <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> is spanned by a three vectors, for example <math>
                        <latex>\StdBss{1} = (1,0,0)</latex>
                     </math>, <math>
                        <latex>\StdBss{2}=(0,1,0)</latex>
                     </math> and <math>
                        <latex>\StdBss{3}=(0,0,1)</latex>
                     </math>. This is so because every vector <math>
                        <latex>\Vect{x}=(a,b,c)</latex>
                     </math> in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> may be expressed as the linear combination</para.body>
               </para>
			            <math.array column="3">
                  <row xmlns:compositor="Compositor" compositor:rowspan="1">
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>(a,b,c)</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="1" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>=</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                     <cell colspan="2" halign="center" valign="middle">
                        <math>
                           <latex>a\cdot \StdBss{1} + b\cdot \StdBss{2} + c\cdot \StdBss{3}</latex>
                        </math>
                     </cell>
                  </row>
               </math.array>
			            <para>
                  <para.body>So if any collection of vectors in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> is to be linearly independent, the number of vectors in the collection must be less than or equal to 3. Accordingly, a collection of four or more vectors in <math>
                        <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>
                     </math> is linearly dependent.</para.body>
               </para>
		          </answer.showme.block.body>
         </answer.showme.block>
      </answer.showme>
	  </showme>
